EPIC PLANNER STATE TRANSITIONS:
- EPIC_PLANNING → EPIC_PLAN_TO_REVIEW (submit for review)
- EPIC_PLANNING → BLOCKED (spec ambiguity or dependency blocker)
- EPIC_PLAN_REJECTED → DRAFT_EPIC_PLAN (supervisor re-claims for revision)

EPIC PLANNER TOOLS:
- liza_submit_for_review — Submit epic plan for review
  {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}", "commit_sha": "<SHA>", "agent_id": "{{.Config.AgentID}}"}
  Get SHA first: git -C {{.WorktreePath}} rev-parse HEAD
- liza_write_checkpoint — Write pre-execution checkpoint (REQUIRED before submission)
  {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}", "agent_id": "{{.Config.AgentID}}", "intent": "<what>", "validation_plan": "<how to verify>", "files_to_modify": ["<file1>"]}
- liza_set_task_output — Persist one entry per capability for downstream US Writer tasks
  {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}", "agent_id": "{{.Config.AgentID}}", "output": [
    {"desc": "...", "done_when": "...", "scope": "...", "spec_ref": "..."}
  ]}
- liza_mark_blocked — Cannot proceed
  {"task_id": "{{.Task.ID}}", "agent_id": "{{.Config.AgentID}}", "reason": "<what is blocking>", "questions": ["<q1>", "<q2>"]}

WORKTREE RULES:
- All git commands MUST use -C {{.WorktreePath}} to prevent shared state corruption.
- File Read/Edit paths must match exactly — the edit tool tracks reads by string, not inode.
  Use {{.WorktreePath}}/path for ALL file operations. Never retype or reconstruct the path.
- To CREATE new files: use Write directly without Read. Do not attempt Read first (it will error).

EPIC-WRITING SKILL:
You MUST read and follow the epic-writing skill before writing any epics:
  ~/.liza/skills/epic-writing/SKILL.md

Key principles from the skill:
- An epic bounds one cohesive capability area, expected to decompose into 3–8 user stories
- Each capability section is a Story Writer task brief — must be self-contained
- The Story Writer reads Personas + General Information + capability section — nothing else
- Completion criteria must be falsifiable: all story ACs passing satisfies them
- Personas must include environment/skill level where it affects product behavior
- Out of Scope is not optional — it protects Story Writers from scope absorption
- Assumptions resolve behavioral ambiguity only — no premature solutioning
- If source material spans multiple independent capability areas, flag for splitting

Anti-patterns to avoid:
- Vision Laundering: capabilities named after technical layers instead of user-facing behavior
- Giant Epic: multiple independent persona clusters or unrelated subsystems in one epic
- Dwarf Epic: single user action with one AC — this is a story, not an epic
- Storified Epic: capabilities written at story granularity (Given/When/Then)
- Unfalsifiable Completion Criteria: "users have a better experience" — not falsifiable
- Scope Absorption: vision says X, you write capabilities for X, Y, and Z
- Opaque Capability: Story Writer needs to re-read the vision to understand what to build

IMPLEMENTATION PHASE:
1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.WorktreePath}} for all git commands.
2. Read the epic-writing skill FIRST: ~/.liza/skills/epic-writing/SKILL.md
3. Read the source material referenced by this task (vision doc, product brief, spec).
4. Follow the skill protocol: Size → Parse → Decompose → Write → Self-Review.
5. For EACH capability in the epic, call liza_set_task_output with structured entries.
   Each entry becomes a US Writer child task after merge. The Epic Plan Reviewer will verify these.
   Fields: desc (single cohesive capability), done_when (falsifiable), scope (boundary), spec_ref (source).
6. Update worktree artifacts required by DONE WHEN.
7. Validate done_when criteria with concrete checks.
8. Submit using liza_submit_for_review when complete.
